Ringgit Trades Near 1997 High on Export Outlook; Bonds Climb

-- B y   D a v i d   Y o n g
-- 
2011-04-04T08:52:51Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-04/ringgit-trades-near-highest-level-since-1997-on-export-outlook.html
Malaysia’s ringgit traded near the
strongest level in more than 13 years on optimism a stronger
recovery in the  U.S. economy  will boost the outlook for exports
and demand for emerging-market assets.  The currency gained in each of the last four months as
developing-nation equity funds attracted  inflows  this year
through March, according to EPFR Global data. A U.S. Labor
Department report on April 1 showed companies in the world’s
largest economy hired 216,000 workers in March, compared with
194,000 in February. Bonds gained.  “The U.S. data has been quite strong, which is good for
the market,” said Azmi Shukri Rahman, a currency trader at CIMB
Investment Bank Bhd. in Kuala Lumpur. “The only thing is that
they will probably still need more data to convince the  Federal
Reserve  to do something about their rates. So the ringgit is
well supported at current levels.”  The ringgit was little changed at 3.0254 per dollar as of
4:32 p.m. in  Kuala Lumpur , according to data compiled by
Bloomberg. The currency has strengthened 1.3 percent this year
and reached 3.0190 on April 1, the strongest level since October
1997.  The U.S. economy expanded at a 3.1 percent annual rate in
the fourth quarter, the Commerce Department said on March 25,
and it may grow 3.1 percent in 2011, the most since 2005, based
on the median of 68 estimates in a Bloomberg News survey.  A Malaysian trade ministry report tomorrow may show exports
increased 5 percent in February compared with a 3 percent gain
the previous month, according to the median forecast in a
Bloomberg News survey. The U.S. bought 10 percent of the
nation’s goods and services last year.  Bond Sales  Developing-nation equity funds attracted inflows of $2.6
billion in the week to March 30, the most since the period ended
Jan. 5, according to EPFR Global. Emerging-market bond funds had
inflows of $2.3 billion in the first quarter, down from $11.5
billion a year earlier.  Malaysia’s benchmark seven-year bonds gained. The yield on
the 4.012 percent note maturing in September 2017 fell one basis
point, or 0.01 percentage point, to 3.87 percent, according to
Bursa Malaysia.  The treasury is scheduled to sell 10- and 15-year bonds
this month via auctions and private offerings, according to its
sale calendar. It raised 24.5 billion ringgit ($8.1 billion) in
the first quarter, a 29 percent increase from a year earlier.  To contact the reporter on this story:
David Yong in  Singapore  at 
 dyong@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
